## Description {#details}

This file defines the SmallPtrSet class.

See the doxygen comment for SmallPtrSetImplBase for more details on the algorithm used.

<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><Highlight kind="comment">/// SmallPtrSetImplBase - This is the common code shared among all the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><Highlight kind="comment">/// SmallPtrSet&lt;&gt;&#39;s, which is almost everything.  SmallPtrSet has two modes, one</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="36"><Highlight kind="comment">/// for small and one for large sets.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="37"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="38"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Small sets use an array of pointers allocated in the SmallPtrSet object,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="39"><Highlight kind="comment">/// which is treated as a simple array of pointers.  When a pointer is added to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00040" /><CodeLine lineNumber="40"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the set, the array is scanned to see if the element already exists, if not</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="41"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the element is &#39;pushed back&#39; onto the array.  If we run out of space in the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="42"><Highlight kind="comment">/// array, we grow into the &#39;large set&#39; case.  SmallSet should be used when the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00043" /><CodeLine lineNumber="43"><Highlight kind="comment">/// sets are often small.  In this case, no memory allocation is used, and only</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00044" /><CodeLine lineNumber="44"><Highlight kind="comment">/// light-weight and cache-efficient scanning is used.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00045" /><CodeLine lineNumber="45"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00046" /><CodeLine lineNumber="46"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Large sets use a classic exponentially-probed hash table.  Empty buckets are</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00047" /><CodeLine lineNumber="47"><Highlight kind="comment">/// represented with an illegal pointer value (-1) to allow null pointers to be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00048" /><CodeLine lineNumber="48"><Highlight kind="comment">/// inserted.  Tombstones are represented with another illegal pointer value</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00049" /><CodeLine lineNumber="49"><Highlight kind="comment">/// (-2), to allow deletion.  The hash table is resized when the table is 3/4 or</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00050" /><CodeLine lineNumber="50"><Highlight kind="comment">/// more.  When this happens, the table is doubled in size.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00051" /><CodeLine lineNumber="51"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
